# CI/CD Pipeline Security Auditor

Structured 6-category security audit against all GitHub Actions workflow files. Covers the same risk categories exploited in real-world supply chain attacks, including the tj-actions/changed-files incident (CVE-2025-30066).

## When to Use

- Audit or review GitHub Actions workflow files
- Scan `.github/workflows/` for security risks
- Detect supply chain attack vectors in CI/CD pipelines
- Find expression injection / script injection vulnerabilities
- Check for dangerous triggers like `pull_request_target`
- Assess pipeline permission hygiene
- Investigate Poisoned Pipeline Execution (PPE) vulnerability

## Instructions

### Step 1 – Locate Workflow Files

```bash
find /path/to/repo/.github/workflows -name "*.yml" -o -name "*.yaml"
# Or clone first:
git clone https://github.com/owner/repo /tmp/target-repo
```

If no `.github/workflows/` directory exists, report no workflows found and stop.

### Step 2 – Run Audit

```bash
pip install -q pyyaml
```

Parse each workflow file and check against the 6 categories below.

### Step 3 – Severity Scale

| Severity | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| CRITICAL | Immediate supply chain or code execution risk |
| HIGH | Exploitable with moderate attacker access |
| MEDIUM | Defense-in-depth gap, should be fixed |
| LOW | Best practice deviation |

### Step 4 – Prioritization Order

1. CRITICAL unpinned third-party actions (direct supply chain vector)
2. HIGH expression injection (direct code execution via PR title/body)
3. HIGH dangerous triggers with checkout (PPE attack surface)
4. HIGH secrets exposure
5. MEDIUM permissions hygiene
6. MEDIUM self-hosted runners
7. MEDIUM GitHub-owned unpinned actions

## 6-Category Check Reference

### Category 1: Unpinned Third-Party Actions (CRITICAL/MEDIUM)

- Detection: `uses:` value contains `@` followed by non-SHA ref (tag, branch name)
- SHA pattern: exactly 40 hex characters
- Third-party (not `actions/` or `github/`) → CRITICAL
- GitHub-owned (`actions/`, `github/`) → MEDIUM

```yaml
# VULNERABLE — tag-pinned
- uses: tj-actions/changed-files@v44

# SAFE — SHA-pinned
- uses: tj-actions/changed-files@d6babd6899969df1a11d14c368283ea4436bca78 # v44
```

### Category 2: Expression Injection (HIGH)

- Detection: `run:` block contains `${{` with user-controlled context values
- Dangerous contexts: `github.event.pull_request.title`, `github.event.pull_request.body`, `github.event.issue.title`, `github.event.comment.body`, `github.head_ref`, `github.event.inputs.*`

```yaml
# VULNERABLE
- run: echo "${{ github.event.pull_request.title }}"

# SAFE — pass via env var
- env:
    PR_TITLE: ${{ github.event.pull_request.title }}
  run: echo "$PR_TITLE"
```

### Category 3: Overly Permissive Permissions (MEDIUM)

- `permissions: write-all` → MEDIUM
- No `permissions:` key at workflow or job level → MEDIUM

```yaml
# SAFE — least-privilege example
permissions:
  contents: read
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
```

### Category 4: Dangerous Triggers (HIGH/MEDIUM)

- `pull_request_target` with checkout of PR head → HIGH
- `pull_request_target` alone → MEDIUM
- `workflow_run` with checkout of triggering PR code → HIGH

```yaml
# VULNERABLE — pull_request_target + checkout of PR head
on:
  pull_request_target:
jobs:
  build:
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          ref: ${{ github.event.pull_request.head.sha }}

# SAFER — use pull_request instead
on:
  pull_request:
```

### Category 5: Secrets Exposure (HIGH/MEDIUM)

- Secrets as CLI args in `run:` block: `${{ secrets.` not inside `env:` → HIGH
- `ACTIONS_RUNNER_DEBUG: true` in env → MEDIUM
- Secrets in step names or echo commands → HIGH

### Category 6: Self-Hosted Runners (MEDIUM/HIGH)

- `runs-on: self-hosted` or `runs-on: [self-hosted, ...]` → MEDIUM
- Combined with `pull_request_target` or untrusted code execution → HIGH

